  "prompt": "Who discovered Avogadro's number?",
  "response": "Avogadro's number, approximately \\(6.022 \\times 10^{23}\\), represents the number of constituent particles (such as atoms or molecules) in one mole of a substance. Although the number is named after the Italian scientist **Amedeo Avogadro**, who proposed the foundational concept in 1811 known as **Avogadro's Law**, he did not calculate its exact value.\n\nThe precise determination of Avogadro's number was achieved through the work of several scientists over the years, with **Jean Perrin**, a French physicist, playing a pivotal role. In the early 20th century, Perrin conducted experiments that provided significant evidence for the atomic theory of matter. Using observations of Brownian motion and applying Albert Einstein's theoretical work on the subject, Perrin was able to estimate the number of particles in a mole of a substance. His meticulous experiments led to a value of Avogadro's number that closely aligns with the modern accepted value.\n\nFor his contributions, Jean Perrin was awarded the **Nobel Prize in Physics in 1926**. His work not only provided a more accurate measurement of Avogadro's number but also offered strong support for the existence of atoms and molecules, solidifying the atomic theory in the scientific community.\n\n**In summary:**\n- **Amedeo Avogadro** proposed the theoretical foundation (Avogadro's Law) but did not determine the numerical value.\n- **Jean Perrin** experimentally calculated Avogadro's number, earning him the Nobel Prize for his contributions.",
